<TITLE> Shahid again blames Sircar for JS dispute </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 11 (bdnews24.com)  Chief whip Abdus Shahid has blamed former speaker Jamiruddin Sircar MP for the initial seating row that sparked a boycott of parliament by the opposition, which came to an end with the return of BNP and its allies to parliament on Thursday. "The former speaker created the problem by distributing seats without any discussion," Shahid told parliament on Thursday replying to an allegation by opposition chief whip Zainal Abdin Farroque. "He (Sircar) is responsible for the conspiracy of making this parliament ineffective," Shahid said. Sircar defended himself by saying that he had mapped out the seat arrangements in line with the rules of procedures He referred to the British House of Commons, Australian parliament and India's Lok Shabha (federal parliament). According to rules of these parliaments, the opposition leaders are to sit at the left side of the speaker while the treasury is seated at the right side. "I distributed seats following this convention. I did not do anything illegal," Sircar said. Parliament convened at around 3pm with speaker Abdul Hamid in the chair. Leader of the opposition and BNP chief Khaleda Zia led her MPs and those of coalition partners into parliament at 3.15pm Thursday after a boycott of 64 days. b
